'''Glycyrrhizol A''' is a [[prenylated]] [[pterocarpan]], a derivative of [[isoflavonoid]]s. It is a compound isolated from the root of the Chinese [[Licorice]] plant (''[[Glycyrrhiza uralensis]]'').
Recent studies by scientists from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] have suggested that these compounds have [[antibacterial]] properties.<ref>{{cite journal | author= He J, Chen L, Shi W, Lu, Q-Y | title=Antibacterial Compounds from ''Glycyrrhiza uralensis'' | journal=[[Journal of Natural Products]] | volume=69| issue=1 | year=2006 | pages=121–124 | id= | doi=10.1021/np058069d | pmid= 16441081}}</ref> The strongest antibacterial activity was observed against ''[[Streptococcus mutans]]'', an organism known to cause tooth decay in humans.
